column6: The medical diagnosis reported by the subject at a study visit. The baseline visit collected information on the subject's medical history prior to the study. Subsequent visits collected information on resource use that included hospitalizations and emergency department (ED) visits.

Relevant for patient's medical history at initial diagnosis, so data should be filtered for timepoint_category=initial_diagnosis to identify rows for comorbidity analysis. MMRF uses the current NCI version of the Charlson Comorbidity index that creates an idex for non-cancer disease diagnoses [https://healthcaredelivery.cancer.gov/seermedicare/considerations/comorbidity.html].
column9:
chd [congestive heart failure]
copd (chronic obstructive pulmonary disease]
cva [cerebrovascular disease]
diabetes
dmendorgan [diabetes with complications]
dementia
mi [myocardial infarction]
mildliver [mild liver]
paralysis [hemiplegia, paraplegia]
peptic [peptic ulcer disease]
pvd [peripheral vascular disease]
renal [renal disease]
rheumatic [rheumatic disease]
aids
column10: Using the NCI Comorbidity index, the clinical events were sorted into the index categories. Of note, very few patients had clinical_events that were associated with the Comorbidity Index.

column6: The medical event during which the clinical diagnosis was made. The "med_hx" diagnoses/events were collected at the baseline of the study. The "ed" diagnoses were made during a visit to the emergency department. The "hosp_admission" diagnoses were made at the time of a hospital admission.
column10: Flag indicating the source of the clinical event. med_hx is assessed at baseline, and the event could have occurred at any point prior to the index_date. ed and hosp_admission are events that occur on or after the index_date; these events relate to either hospital admission [hosp_admission] or emergency room visit [ed]. These events will have overlap.
